# Coding Practice Standards

## TypeScript & NestJS Conventions

### File Naming
- Use **kebab-case** for all file names: `employee.service.ts`, `create-employee.dto.ts`
- Use **PascalCase** for class names: `EmployeeService`, `CreateEmployeeDto`
- Entity files: `{entity-name}.entity.ts` (e.g., `employee.entity.ts`)
- DTO files: `{action}-{entity}.dto.ts` (e.g., `create-employee.dto.ts`, `update-employee.dto.ts`)
- Module files: `{module-name}.module.ts`
- Service files: `{module-name}.service.ts`
- Controller files: `{module-name}.controller.ts`

### Import Organization
1. External packages (NestJS, third-party)
2. Internal modules (relative imports from other modules)
3. Local imports (from same module)
4. Type imports (use `import type` when appropriate)

Example:
```typescript
import { Injectable, NotFoundException } from '@nestjs/common';
import { InjectRepository } from '@nestjs/typeorm';
import { Repository } from 'typeorm';
import { Employee } from './entities/employee.entity';
import { CreateEmployeeDto } from './dto/create-employee.dto';
```

### Code Formatting
- Use 2 spaces for indentation
- Use single quotes for strings (unless string contains single quotes)
- Use trailing commas in multi-line objects/arrays
- Maximum line length: 120 characters
- Always use semicolons
- Use `async/await` instead of `.then()/.catch()` chains

### TypeScript Best Practices
- Always define return types for functions
- Use `interface` for object shapes, `type` for unions/intersections
- Avoid `any` - use `unknown` if type is truly unknown
- Use strict null checks where possible
- Prefer `const` over `let`, avoid `var`
- Use optional chaining (`?.`) and nullish coalescing (`??`) appropriately

### NestJS Patterns
- All services must be decorated with `@Injectable()`
- Use dependency injection via constructor
- Prefer async methods for all service methods
- Use NestJS built-in exceptions (NotFoundException, BadRequestException, etc.)
- Keep controllers thin - business logic belongs in services

### Code Organization
- One class per file
- Group related functionality in modules
- Keep files focused and under 300 lines when possible
- Extract complex logic into private methods
- Use meaningful variable and function names

### Comments
- Use JSDoc comments for public methods
- Explain "why" not "what" in comments
- Keep comments up-to-date with code changes
- Remove commented-out code before committing
